    <summary>The Bitcoin DNS seed infrastructure has been facing instability issues due to a custom DNS implementation that is not fully compatible and has had bugs in the past. The issue was brought up by various individuals, including Alex Kotenko, who suggested setting up BIND forwarding requests to two dnsseeds running on separate ports. However, Jeff Garzik argued against this idea, stating that using the bind/zone-xfer system would result in fewer total addresses going through to the clients. Andreas Schildbach raised concerns about the reliability of DNS seed and suggested maintaining a quality infrastructure as the first step towards addressing the issue.There have been reports of SERVFAIL errors with some of the seeds, such as dnsseed.bitcoin.dashjr.org and testnet-seed.bitcoin.petertodd.org, when tested by different ISPs. Even large ISPs like British Telecom and Telefonica are unable to access these servers. The current state of Bitcoin DNS seeds shows that some are okay while others have SERVFAIL issues, one is tried multiple ISPs and one only returns one node. Gregory Maxwell suggests that relying exclusively on DNS seeds increases isolation vulnerabilities and that clients should be robust regarding DNS lookups.Despite the issues, there are efforts to improve the situation. Robert McKay suggested configuring bind as a DNS forwarder in a zone context, which can forward different zones to different dnsseed daemons running on different non-public IPs or different ports on the same IP. There are also pull requests outstanding to include hard-coded seed peers and getaddr sourced IPs, which will provide more backup paths once they are merged in. Additionally, the writer mentions that their android wallet is working "OK" despite some temporary availability problems with seeds.The discussion in the email chain is about setting up BIND forwarding for DNS seeds for the bitcoin network. There are issues with testnet DNS seed as it only returns one IP address, wher